mented': True, 'context': ["Kispiox Mountain | Kispiox Mountain is the highest mountain in the Kispiox Range of the Hazelton Mountains in northern British Columbia, Canada, located northwest of the junction of Kispiox River and Skeena River. It has a prominence of 1561 m , created by the Kispiox-Nass Pass, thus making it one of Canada's many ultra-prominent peaks.", 'Tsaydaychuz Peak | Tsaydaychuz Peak, 2758 m (9049 feet), prominence below Howson Peak is 1826 m, is a mountain in the Pattullo Range of the Hazelton Mountains, the southernmost subdivision of the Northern Interior Mountains system of the British Columbia Interior. The Pattullo Range, of which Tsaydaychuz is the highest summit, is located south of Tesla and Eutsuk Lakes and to the north of the Dean River. To its east is the Nechako Plateau.', 'Shedin Peak | Shedin Peak is the highest mountain in the Atna Range and in the Skeena Mountains of northern British Columbia, Canada, located 77 km north of Hazelton at the head of Rosenthal Creek. It has a prominence of 1798 m , created by the Bear-Driftwood Pass.'], 'question': 'Which mountain range contains the highest rise of the Hazel River?', 'reasoning': 'The question asks about the "highest rise of the Hazel River" and the mountain range it\'s in. The provided context mentions "Hazelton Mountains" and "Hazelton" but does not contain any information about a "Hazel River" or its source/rise. Therefore, a search is needed to find information about the Hazel River and its geographical location, specifically its highest point or source.', 'search_query': '"Hazel River source" OR "Hazel River highest point" OR "Hazel River mountain range"'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['The Flirtations (group) | The Flirtations were a pro-LGBT a cappella musical group active from 1988 to 1997. Their music provided an opportunity for both a celebration of gay culture and a call to arms in the battle against AIDS and homophobia. They were fronted by the gay activist Michael Callen from establishment in 1988 until his death in 1993. The Flirtations performed at a number of prominent national venues, and performed a song in the soundtrack to "Philadelphia".', "Flirtation Walk | Flirtation Walk is a 1934 romantic musical film written by Delmer Daves and Lou Edelman, and directed by Frank Borzage. It focuses on a soldier (Dick Powell) who falls in love with a general's daughter (Ruby Keeler) during the general's brief stop in Hawaii, but she leaves with her father for the Philippines before their relationship can blossom. They are re-united several years later when the soldier is about to graduate from West Point and the general becomes the Academy's Commandant.", 'Flirt (1995 film) | Flirt is a 1995 drama film written and directed by Hal Hartley.'], 'question': 'The Flirtations performed at a number of prominent national venues, and performed a song in the soundtrack to a 1993 American drama film written by who? ', 'reasoning': 'The question asks for the writer of the 1993 American drama film whose soundtrack featured a song by The Flirtations. Context [1] states that The Flirtations performed a song in the soundtrack to "Philadelphia". Therefore, I need to find out who wrote the film "Philadelphia".', 'search_query': 'who wrote the film Philadelphia 1993'}) (input_keys=None)]

'generate_answer.predict' predictor demos: [Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['Mack Brown | William Mack Brown (born August 27, 1951) is a former American college football coach. He was most recently head football coach of the Texas Longhorns football team of the University of Texas at Austin. He is currently a college football commentator for ESPN.', 'Mack Brown (running back) | Mack Brown (born September 24, 1991) is an American football running back for the Washington Redskins of the National Football League (NFL). He played college football at Florida. Brown signed with the Houston Texans as an undrafted free agent in 2015.', 'Watson Brown | Lester Watson Brown (born April 19, 1950) is a retired American football coach and former player. He was most recently the head football coach at Tennessee Technological University, a position he held from 2007 to 2015. Previously, Brown served as the head coach at Austin Peay State University (1979–1980), the University of Cincinnati (1983), Rice University (1984–1985), Vanderbilt University (1986–1990), and the University of Alabama at Birmingham (1995–2006). He was also the athletic director at Rice from 1984 to 1985 and at UAB from 2002 to 2005. Brown played college football as a quarterback at Vanderbilt. He is the older brother of Mack Brown, the former head football coach at the University of Texas at Austin.', 'None (Meshuggah EP) | None is an EP by Swedish metal band Meshuggah. It was released on November 8, 1994, by Nuclear Blast. The band started embracing a more complex approach that would lay the grounds for their later style. The EP is out of print, but the first four tracks are also available on the "Contradictions Collapse" reissue while the fifth track is on the "Destroy Erase Improve" reissue. This is the band\'s first release to feature rhythm guitarist Mårten Hagström.', 'None (Cloak of Altering EP) | None is an EP by Cloak of Altering, independently released on November 18, 2013.', 'Nonea | Nonea is a genus of the borage family Boraginaceae. Sometimes known as monkswort, these are perennial or annual herbs.'], 'question': 'What job does the former American college football coach, who coached the 2004 Texas Longhorns football team, currently hold?', 'reasoning': 'The question asks for the current job of a former American college football coach who coached the Texas Longhorns.\nContext [1] identifies "Mack Brown" as a "former American college football coach" who "was most recently head football coach of the Texas Longhorns football team of the University of Texas at Austin." This matches the description of the person.\nContext [1] also states his current job: "He is currently a college football commentator for ESPN."\nContext [3] further confirms that Mack Brown was the "former head football coach at the University of Texas at Austin."\nThe other entries are either about a different person (a running back, or Watson Brown who did not coach Texas) or irrelevant topics.\n\nTherefore, the person in question is Mack Brown, and his current job is a college football commentator for ESPN.', 'answer': 'College football commentator for ESPN'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ["Kispiox Mountain | Kispiox Mountain is the highest mountain in the Kispiox Range of the Hazelton Mountains in northern British Columbia, Canada, located northwest of the junction of Kispiox River and Skeena River. It has a prominence of 1561 m , created by the Kispiox-Nass Pass, thus making it one of Canada's many ultra-prominent peaks.", 'Tsaydaychuz Peak | Tsaydaychuz Peak, 2758 m (9049 feet), prominence below Howson Peak is 1826 m, is a mountain in the Pattullo Range of the Hazelton Mountains, the southernmost subdivision of the Northern Interior Mountains system of the British Columbia Interior. The Pattullo Range, of which Tsaydaychuz is the highest summit, is located south of Tesla and Eutsuk Lakes and to the north of the Dean River. To its east is the Nechako Plateau.', 'Shedin Peak | Shedin Peak is the highest mountain in the Atna Range and in the Skeena Mountains of northern British Columbia, Canada, located 77 km north of Hazelton at the head of Rosenthal Creek. It has a prominence of 1798 m , created by the Bear-Driftwood Pass.', "Hazel River | The Hazel River is a 47.8 mi tributary of the Rappahannock River in northern Virginia in the United States. Via the Rappahannock, it is part of the Chesapeake Bay watershed. It rises in Shenandoah National Park and flows generally eastwardly through Rappahannock and Culpeper counties. It joins the Rappahannock River from the west about 3 mi northwest of Remington. The Hazel's largest tributaries are the Hughes River, which joins it at the border of Rappahannock and Culpeper counties, and the Thornton River, which joins it in Culpeper County.", "Hazel Creek (Great Smoky Mountains) | Hazel Creek is a tributary stream of the Little Tennessee River in the southwestern Great Smoky Mountains of North Carolina. The creek's bottomlands were home to several pioneer Appalachian communities and logging towns before its incorporation into the Great Smoky Mountains National Park. Hazel Creek is now a back country campsite and historical area.", 'Hazelton Mountains | The Hazelton Mountains are a grouping of mountain ranges on the inland lee of the Kitimat Ranges of the Coast Mountains in northwestern British Columbia, Canada, spanning the area of Hazelton south to the Nechako Reservoir. Defined by the British Columbia geographic names office, they span from the Nass River to the Nechako Plateau, and between the Coast Mountains and the Bulkley River, they are considered by geographers to be part of the Interior Mountains complex, though in local perspective they are considered to be part of the Coast Mountains. They are neighboured on the west by the Kitimat Ranges and on the east by the southernmost section of the Skeena Mountains; beyond the Nass River, which is their northern boundary, are the Boundary Ranges of the Coast Mountains. To their southeast is the Nechako Plateau, including the Quanchus Range on the near-island between Ootsa and Eutsuk Lakes of the Nechako Reservoir (the Quanchus may be considered to be part of the Hazelton Mountains in some classification systems).'], 'question': 'Which mountain range contains the highest rise of the Hazel River?', 'reasoning': 'The question asks for the mountain range containing the highest rise of the Hazel River.\nDocument [4] states that the "Hazel River... rises in Shenandoah National Park".\nShenandoah National Park is located within the Blue Ridge Mountains.\nTherefore, the Blue Ridge Mountains contain the highest rise of the Hazel River.\nNone of the provided documents explicitly state "Blue Ridge Mountains", but they do state where the river rises, and that location is within a known mountain range. The other documents discuss different geographical locations (British Columbia, Great Smoky Mountains) and different water bodies (Hazel Creek).', 'answer': 'Blue Ridge Mountains'}) (input_keys=None), Example({'augmented': True, 'context': ['The Flirtations (group) | The Flirtations were a pro-LGBT a cappella musical group active from 1988 to 1997. Their music provided an opportunity for both a celebration of gay culture and a call to arms in the battle against AIDS and homophobia. They were fronted by the gay activist Michael Callen from establishment in 1988 until his death in 1993. The Flirtations performed at a number of prominent national venues, and performed a song in the soundtrack to "Philadelphia".', "Flirtation Walk | Flirtation Walk is a 1934 romantic musical film written by Delmer Daves and Lou Edelman, and directed by Frank Borzage. It focuses on a soldier (Dick Powell) who falls in love with a general's daughter (Ruby Keeler) during the general's brief stop in Hawaii, but she leaves with her father for the Philippines before their relationship can blossom. They are re-united several years later when the soldier is about to graduate from West Point and the general becomes the Academy's Commandant.", 'Flirt (1995 film) | Flirt is a 1995 drama film written and directed by Hal Hartley.', 'Philadelphia (film) | Philadelphia is a 1993 American drama film and one of the first mainstream Hollywood films to acknowledge HIV/AIDS, homosexuality, and homophobia. It was written by Ron Nyswaner, directed by Jonathan Demme and stars Tom Hanks and Denzel Washington.', 'Streets of Philadelphia | "Streets of Philadelphia" is a song written and performed by American rock musician Bruce Springsteen for the film "Philadelphia" (1993), an early mainstream film dealing with HIV/AIDS. Released as a single in 1994, the song was a hit in many countries, particularly Canada, France, Germany, Ireland and Norway, where it topped the singles charts.', "Money for Nothing (1993 film) | Money for Nothing is a 1993 American comedy crime film directed by Ramón Menéndez. It is based on a reporter's article about the life of Joey Coyle, an unemployed longshoreman in Philadelphia who, on February 26, 1981, found $1.2 million in the middle of the street after it had fallen out of the back of an armored car. The screenplay, written by Menéndez, Tom Musca and Carol Sobieski, is based on an article by Mark Bowden. The film stars John Cusack as Coyle, and features a supporting cast that includes Debi Mazar, Michael Madsen, Benicio del Toro, Michael Rapaport, James Gandolfini, Philip Seymour Hoffman, Maury Chaykin, Currie Graham and Fionnula Flanagan."], 'question': 'The Flirtations performed at a number of prominent national venues, and performed a song in the soundtrack to a 1993 American drama film written by who? ', 'reasoning': '1. The question asks about a 1993 American drama film whose soundtrack included a song by The Flirtations, and specifically asks who wrote it.\n2. Context [1] states that "The Flirtations... performed a song in the soundtrack to \'Philadelphia\'".\n3. Context [4] describes "Philadelphia (film)" as a "1993 American drama film" and explicitly states, "It was written by Ron Nyswaner".\n4. Therefore, the writer of the film is Ron Nyswaner.', 'answer': 'Ron Nyswaner'}) (input_keys=None)]

